Justinian further enacted that in plus petitio re the judge should condemn the defendant, so far as he found him liable, and the plaintih' in three times the excess of fees exacted from the other by the ‘executor' through the overclaim (ξ 24 supr.). Plus petitio loco could no longer prejudice the defendant, because the judge was bound to apply the principles of the actio de eo quod certo loco, and either condemn the defendant to discharge his obligation at the place agreed upon, or make allowance for the loss and inconvenience he suffered by having to pay elsewhere; and plus petitio causa was equally harmless.
